The author emphasizes the importance of increasing manufacturing in the United States to prevent supply disruptions and price spikes for American families. They argue that by producing more domestically, supply chains become more resilient and less susceptible to disruptions, such as those experienced during the pandemic. The author states that their economic plan prioritizes American manufacturing and resilient supply chains, leading to a significant growth in the sector. They claim that since taking office, 545,000 manufacturing jobs have been added, making 2021 the year with the highest number of manufacturing jobs created in almost 30 years. The author attributes this success to their economic plan, which aims to grow the economy from the bottom up and middle out. They urge Congress to pass the Bipartisan Innovation Act to further lower prices and promote innovation and advanced manufacturing within the United States.